Hi Torgeir

> when using reference to a memorylocation ?beginfile, ?endoffile
> etc, i was wondering if it's possible to do this in a way using variables, so
> you can use a for-next sentence instead of writing this over and over for dozens
> of files.  ?

You could probably do it with a macro. I've attached what I came up with, but I 
don't use macros much in Blitz, and I can't remember how to use the ~ operator 
in macros. So you'll find that the code attached will not work, but I'm sure 
it's the right idea if someone can fix it.

; ---------8<------------8<----------
Macro GetLabel
	?label~1~
End Macro

For i.w=0 To 3
	NPrint "Label ",i," is at address ",!GetLabel{}
Next
ClickMouse
End

label0:
Dc.b "This is label 0",0
Even
label1:
Dc.b "This is label 1",0
Even
label2:
Dc.b "This is label 2",0
Even
label3:
Dc.b "This is label 3",0
Even
; ---------8<------------8<----------

> I'm incbin'ing text files, and then write them to ram: and then read them 
> into arrays.

You can probably do this easier if you don't write to a file in RAM: first. If 
they are just plain text files which you have included, then you can just read 
straight from the memory location into the array.

However, if it is e.g. files of numbers which you want to read in as numbers 
rather than just a sequence of characters, then writing to a file then reading 
from a file probably is the best solution.

> Also I want to incbin intuifonts and write these to ram: and then load them, but
> the loading command seems to only read in the fonts: dir.  Is there any way to
> get around this?

You should be able to specify the full path to the font file. However, if the 
font is already resident in memory, that will be used. Also, in the .font file 
the path to the actual font bitmaps is stored. If these are hardcoded to use 
fonts: then it will always load them (they mostly/should only have relative 
pathnames though).


