From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@...>
Date: 03-14-01 17:28:06
Subject: @{b}Re: Run on GfxCards...@{ub}

Hi Thorsten

> Problem 1:
> ==========
> How to get it work on Gfx-Cards in all kind of ScreenModes?  Does
> someone  have  a  nice  example of a ScreenModeSelector (maybe by
> using NCommands or SystemCommands for small executeable?)

Attached is an example for the NCS of using a screen mode requester and then 
opening a screen and doing some drawing to it. It is not a fast way of doing 
double buffering on a GFX card though.

> Problem 2:
> ==========
> Is  there any way to use NScreen, NBitmap, NPalette as replacement for this
> example...   Is  there  any replace for ScreensBitmap ???  I want to make a very
>  small  executeable...   Examples  are very welcome...  Many thanks in advance!

In the above you do not need to use ScreensBitMap - you have already created 2 
bitmaps for drawing onto, which then get copied to the screen bitmap. So you do 
not want to grab the screen's bitmap as bitmap 0.

If you need to copy the data from the screen bitmap onto a bitmap used for 
drawing using the NCS, you can do something like:

*scr.Screen = NScreenID
*rp.RastPort = NBitMapRastPort
BltBitMapRastPort_ *scr\RastPort\BitMap,0,0,*rp,0,0,*scr\Width,*scr\Height,$C0

(assuming the bitmap and screen are the same size)

I know this is not the same as what ScreensBitMap does - that command fills in 
a BitMap object with the information about the bitmap of the screen. As I have 
said, you did not need to do this with this program. However, if you really 
want to do this with the NCS, what you need to do is create the bitmaps BEFORE 
you open the screen, and pass the extra Tag (to the NScreen command) 
#SA_BitMap,NBitMapID.


